Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.915 --> 00:00:08.695
How to Encourage Seniors with Eating Problems to Eat More

00:00:10.795 --> 00:00:12.605
For Seniors with Poor Appetite

00:00:13.940 --> 00:00:18.840
In older people, loss of appetite can often point to a major illness.

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:26.000
The first thing to do when the senior stops eating or shows a decline in interest in food is to find the cause.

00:00:27.900 --> 00:00:30.940
Treating the underlying cause can often help a person regain some appetite.

00:00:33.340 --> 00:00:37.320
Bringing the senior to a doctor to get to the bottom of the issue and find the cause

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:38.720
is a good first step.

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:43.620
While treating the underlying cause of the appetite problem,

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:48.100
there are things one can do to encourage the senior to eat or to stimulate their appetite.

00:00:50.240 --> 00:00:51.740
Evaluate the Environment

00:00:53.520 --> 00:00:56.880
First, assess the environment and layout of the area where the senior eats.

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:02.140
If there’s a lot of noise in the room or if the light is too dim,

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:04.980
it can make it difficult for the senior to focus on eating.

00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:09.200
This is particularly true for person with dementia.

00:01:11.135 --> 00:01:13.535
Create an inviting atmosphere for meals.

00:01:14.845 --> 00:01:17.195
Turn off the radio or TV.

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:19.900
If the senior is living in residential home,

00:01:19.900 --> 00:01:22.320
see if it is possible for him or her to eat in the room,

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:25.280
rather than in a crowded, busy dining area.

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:30.780
If the eating area is dark, open the curtains or turn on a light.

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:36.420
In some cases, a room that’s too bright or that has sharp, glaring lamps

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:37.700
can make it difficult for a person to eat.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:44.540
Change the position of lights if they are shining in a person’s eyes or directly on the table.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:48.440
Choose the Food with Care

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:54.660
Getting the senior to eat is about offering quality, not quantity.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.560
It is better to offer nutrient-rich, healthy choices

00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:01.720
than to provide high calorie, high-fat junk food.

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:06.660
Often, serving smaller meals more frequently can help a senior regain his or her appetite.

00:02:08.700 --> 00:02:12.340
Limiting the choices available can also help resolve a loss of appetite in elderly people.

00:02:14.300 --> 00:02:18.780
When there’s too much available, it’s easy for a person, especially someone with cognitive decline,

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:19.880
to become overwhelmed by it all.

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:23.820
Along with providing the seniors with the right food,

00:02:24.360 --> 00:02:28.220
be sure to make water available at all meals and throughout the day.

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:33.500
People are less likely to eat when they feel dehydrated,

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:37.240
and older adults often have difficulty detecting thirst.

00:02:38.925 --> 00:02:41.155
Make meals an occasion

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:48.000
It can be difficult for a person who lives alone or in a residential home to get excited about eating.

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.420
But if you work with the seniors to make regularly scheduled meals an event,

00:02:52.595 --> 00:02:54.725
they are going to be more likely to want to eat.

00:02:55.795 --> 00:02:57.705
Schedule regular mealtimes each day.

00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:03.780
You can do a traditional three meal day or have five or six smaller mealtimes.

00:03:05.120 --> 00:03:10.720
If the senior has stopped eating, get to the bottom of it and get any medical conditions under control.

00:03:12.080 --> 00:03:17.160
Once you know why a senior has lost his or her appetite, you can work out how to get that person eating again.

